## Modern React Architecture Patterns

Building a production-ready React application isn’t just about writing functional components—it’s about creating a system that scales, remains maintainable, and adapts to changing requirements. As your app grows, how you organize code, separate concerns, and structure components becomes just as important as the features themselves.

In this chapter, we’ll explore **modern React architecture patterns** that help you build robust, scalable applications. We’ll focus on three key areas:

- Component composition and separation of concerns
- The Container/Presentational pattern
- Feature-based folder organization

By the end, you’ll have a clear blueprint for structuring your React codebase like a professional.

---

## 1. Component Composition: Building with Reusability and Clarity

React is built on the principle of **composition**—combining simple, focused components to create complex UIs. This approach encourages reusability, clarity, and maintainability.

### Why Composition Matters

Instead of building monolithic components that handle everything (data fetching, rendering, logic), you break them into smaller, single-purpose pieces. This makes your code easier to test, debug, and extend.

For example, consider a `UserProfile` component that displays a user’s avatar, name, and bio. A poorly structured version might look like this:

```jsx
function UserProfile({ user }) {
  const [isEditing, setIsEditing] = useState(false);

  const handleSave = () => {
    // API call to update user
  };

  return (
    <div>
      {isEditing ? (
        <input value={user.name} onChange={(e) => setUser({ ...user, name: e.target.value })} />
      ) : (
        <h2>{user.name}</h2>
      )}
      <img src={user.avatar} alt="User" />
      <p>{user.bio}</p>
      {isEditing ? (
        <button onClick={handleSave}>Save</button>
      ) : (
        <button onClick={() => setIsEditing(true)}>Edit</button>
      )}
    </div>
  );
}
```

This component handles rendering, state, and logic all at once. It’s hard to reuse, test, and maintain.

### Refactored with Composition

Let’s refactor using composition:

```jsx
// UserAvatar.js
function UserAvatar({ src, alt }) {
  return <img src={src} alt={alt} />;
}

// UserName.js
function UserName({ name, editable, onChange }) {
  if (editable) {
    return <input value={name} onChange={onChange} />;
  }
  return <h2>{name}</h2>;
}

// UserBio.js
function UserBio({ bio }) {
  return <p>{bio}</p>;
}

// UserActions.js
function UserActions({ isEditing, onEdit, onSave }) {
  return isEditing ? (
    <button onClick={onSave}>Save</button>
  ) : (
    <button onClick={onEdit}>Edit</button>
  );
}

// UserProfile.js (composition root)
function UserProfile({ user }) {
  const [isEditing, setIsEditing] = useState(false);
  const [editedUser, setEditedUser] = useState(user);

  const handleSave = () => {
    // Update user logic
    setIsEditing(false);
  };

  return (
    <div>
      <UserAvatar src={editedUser.avatar} alt="User" />
      <UserName
        name={editedUser.name}
        editable={isEditing}
        onChange={(e) => setEditedUser({ ...editedUser, name: e.target.value })}
      />
      <UserBio bio={editedUser.bio} />
      <UserActions
        isEditing={isEditing}
        onEdit={() => setIsEditing(true)}
        onSave={handleSave}
      />
    </div>
  );
}
```

Now, each component has a single responsibility. `UserAvatar` only renders an image, `UserName` handles display or editing, and `UserActions` manages the interaction. This makes testing and reuse much easier.

> ✅ **Pro Tip**: Use **children props** or **render props** to create flexible, reusable components. For example:
> ```jsx
> <Card>
>   {(props) => <CardHeader {...props} />}
> </Card>
> ```

---

## 2. Container/Presentational Pattern: Separating Logic from Presentation

One of the most powerful architectural patterns in React is the **Container/Presentational** pattern. It separates components into two categories:

- **Presentational Components**: Concerned with *how things look*. They receive data via props and emit events.
- **Container Components**: Concerned with *how things work*. They fetch data, manage state, and pass it to presentational components.

This separation makes your code more predictable and easier to test.

### Example: User List

Let’s build a `UserList` feature.

#### Poor Structure (Mixed Concerns)

```jsx
function UserList() {
  const [users, setUsers] = useState([]);
  const [loading, setLoading] = useState(true);
  const [error, setError] = useState(null);

  useEffect(() => {
    fetch('/api/users')
      .then(res => res.json())
      .then(data => {
        setUsers(data);
        setLoading(false);
      })
      .catch(err => {
        setError(err.message);
        setLoading(false);
      });
  }, []);

  if (loading) return <Spinner />;
  if (error) return <ErrorMessage message={error} />;

  return (
    <div>
      <h1>Users</h1>
      <ul>
        {users.map(user => (
          <li key={user.id}>{user.name}</li>
        ))}
      </ul>
    </div>
  );
}
```

This component does everything: data fetching, state management, and rendering.

#### Refactored with Container/Presentational

```jsx
// UserListContainer.js
function UserListContainer() {
  const [users, setUsers] = useState([]);
  const [loading, setLoading] = useState(true);
  const [error, setError] = useState(null);

  useEffect(() => {
    fetch('/api/users')
      .then(res => res.json())
      .then(data => {
        setUsers(data);
        setLoading(false);
      })
      .catch(err => {
        setError(err.message);
        setLoading(false);
      });
  }, []);

  return (
    <UserList users={users} loading={loading} error={error} />
  );
}

// UserList.js (Presentational)
function UserList({ users, loading, error }) {
  if (loading) return <Spinner />;
  if (error) return <ErrorMessage message={error} />;

  return (
    <div>
      <h1>Users</h1>
      <ul>
        {users.map(user => (
          <li key={user.id}>{user.name}</li>
        ))}
      </ul>
    </div>
  );
}
```

Now:
- `UserListContainer` manages data fetching and state.
- `UserList` only renders what it receives.

This makes `UserList` reusable. You could use it with different containers:
```jsx
<UserList users={mockUsers} />
```

> ✅ **Best Practice**: Use hooks like `useState`, `useEffect`, and custom hooks inside containers. Presentational components should be **dumb**—they only care about props.

---

## 3. Feature-Based Folder Organization: Scaling Your Codebase

As your app grows, a flat structure like `components/`, `pages/`, `utils/` becomes unmanageable. A **feature-based** or **domain-driven** organization groups files by feature, not by type.

### Example: E-commerce App

Instead of:
```
src/
  components/
    Button.js
    Card.js
  pages/
    HomePage.js
    ProductPage.js
  utils/
    api.js
```

Use:
```
src/
  features/
    auth/
      components/
        LoginForm.js
        RegisterForm.js
      hooks/
        useAuth.js
      services/
        authApi.js
      index.js
    products/
      components/
        ProductCard.js
        ProductList.js
      hooks/
        useProducts.js
      services/
        productApi.js
      pages/
        ProductPage.js
      index.js
  App.js
  index.js
```

Each feature (`auth`, `products`) is self-contained. It includes:
- Components
- Hooks
- API services
- Pages (if needed)

This makes it easier to:
- Locate related code
- Reuse features
- Lazy-load modules
- Onboard new developers

> ✅ **Tip**: Use an `index.js` file in each feature to expose public APIs (e.g., `export { useAuth } from './hooks/useAuth'`). This creates a clean interface.

---

## Real-World Example: GitHub Profile Viewer

Let’s apply these patterns to a GitHub profile viewer app.

### Structure

```
src/
  features/
    profile/
      components/
        ProfileAvatar.js
        ProfileBio.js
        ProfileStats.js
      hooks/
        useGitHubProfile.js
      services/
        githubApi.js
      pages/
        ProfilePage.js
      index.js
```

### Code Snippets

